  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "There is a tension in Emilie Du Châtelet's thought on mathematics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "The objects of mathematics are ideal or fictional entities; nevertheless, mathematics is presented as indispensable for an account of the physical world.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Du Châtelet has a worked-out defense of the explanatory and epistemic need for mathematical objects, consistent with their metaphysical non-fundamentality.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Christian Wolff, arguably the most influential German philosopher of the early eighteenth century, was also ambivalent about mathematical physics.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Wolff considers definitions in mathematics to be models of clarity and distinctness.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Wolff is pessimistic about the role of mathematics in causal explanation, stressing that explanations ought to track how things are in themselves ('was in den Sachen selbst liege'), at the level of fundamental simple substances.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Given these commitments, we might expect Du Châtelet to follow Wolff and deny that Newtonian physics can track the real causal structure of the world without supplementation.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Instead, she is optimistic about mathematical physics.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "With no resort to it, one would hope in vain to make great progress in the study of nature.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "It is the key to all discoveries; and if there are still several inexplicable things in physics, that is because geometry has been insufficiently used to explain them, and one has perhaps not yet gone far enough in this science.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Propositions referring to imaginary mathematical objects can thus yield a true theory (if not the full details of its application to actual phenomena).",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "This example shows that, for Du Châtelet, abstract representations that do not truly represent empirical reality can still play a role in correct reasoning.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "What matters is whether the reasoning in question leads to empirically accurate conclusions, and not whether each of its premises is strictly speaking true.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Du Châtelet contends that that all the sciences 'must' employ abstract mathematical notions both in the context of discovering laws or principles-this is the 'art d'inventer' or ars inveniendi-and to address problems that cannot be solved by the unaided understanding.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Breaking with Wolff, Du Châtelet argues that the objects of metaphysics can be conceived only by the understanding, and not the imagination.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "But it is precisely the imagination, and the spatiotemporal properties it deals with, that are needed for making determinate claims about actual bodies.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "I have argued that despite her broadly Wolffian metaphysics, Du Châtelet is far more optimistic than Wolff about the explanatory and epistemic status of mathematics, and that this position is linked to core features of her metaphysics and epistemology.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
